<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fourth Round of Textile Talks to Begin 15 Jan </TI></H3>
<H4>   PRC Trade Chairman `Expects' Results </H4>
<F P=102> HK1401050094 Hong Kong LIEN HO PAO in Chinese 14 Jan 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> HK1401050094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong LIEN HO PAO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporter Teng Mei-ling (6772 5019 3781) from Beijing: </F>
"Zheng Hongye Criticizes the United States for Making a Mountain 
Out of a Molehill"] 
  [Text] Zheng Hongye, chairman of the China Council for the 
Promotion of International Trade, criticized the United States 
yesterday for having "made a mountain out of a molehill" on the 
issue of Chinese textile import. Although Zheng expressed the 
hope that the Sino-U.S. talks in two days time would be a 
complete success, he stressed that the mainland has a very big 
trading market. Anyway, "if not in the east, then in the west," 
he said. 
  When answering reporters' questions at a closed-door meeting 
of the Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Strait 
[ARATS] in Beijing yesterday, Zheng Hongye said: U.S. trade 
makes up only a small portion of the mainland's total foreign 
trade volume and is "not worth mentioning." 
  He stressed that there are different views and opinions 
between China and the United States and the two sides have held 
several talks on the textiles issue. He believed, provided both 
sides observe the principle of "equality and mutual benefit," 
the problem will not be hard to resolve. However, if one keeps 
only itself in mind, it will be very hard to resolve the issue. 
  He refuted the U.S. criticism that the mainland is not 
opening its market, saying that the it has never closed its 
doors to the U.S. market. What actually happened is that the 
mainland wanted to import some commodities from the United 
States, the latter refused to offer. But he did not clearly 
point out what the commodities were. 
  On the forthcoming Sino-U.S. meeting on the textiles issue, 
which will be held from 15 to 17 January, Zheng Hongye stressed 
that he was confident that substantive results would be achieved. 
  He also said, if the United States insisted on imposing 
economic sanctions on the mainland, the development of bilateral 
trade would be harmed. Anyway, he said, if the United States 
really imposes economic sanctions, the mainland still has many 
trade markets outside, "if not in the east, then in the west." 

</TEXT>

