<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official on Asia Pacific Political Security </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1401125494 Beijing XINHUA in English 1057 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1401125494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Manila, January 14 (XINHUA) -- China will continue 
to make efforts in maintaining the political stability and 
economic prosperity in Asia and the Pacific region, a visiting 
Chinese congresswoman said here today. 
  Lin Liyun, head of a Chinese congressional delegation, made 
the commitment in her speech at the second general meeting of 
the Asia- Pacific Parliamentary Forum which opened here today. 
  Lin, member of the Standing Committee of the National 
People's Congress of China, said many Asia-Pacific countries 
have proposed to set up an Asia-Pacific security mechanism which 
fully demonstrates a cherished aspiration of various countries 
to maintain peace, stability and security in the region. 
  However, she said, China holds that the establishment of any 
security mechanism must be in line with the regional diversities 
and complexities. 
  "Only such an initiative proceeds from the actual conditions 
and special characteristics in this region, can it enjoy the 
support by the most of the countries," she added. 
  The congresswoman said China will "continue bilaterally and 
regionally multi-tier, multi-channel and multi-form 
consultations and discussions with the parties concerned on this 
issue." 
  As for the economic development, Lin said the rapid growth 
momentum of Asia and the Pacific region had not been strangled 
by the dramatic changes of the world's political pattern. 
  With the sustained economic growth for many years, the 
average increase this year for the whole region is still 
estimated above 7 percent, much higher than the projections for 
the rest of the world. 
  Lin said the rapid development of different kinds of 
economic 
cooperations would enhance the stability in the region and lay a 
solid foundation to a comparative stability in the whole Asia- 
Pacific region. 
  While recognizing that peace, stability and economic 
development will remain a main stream of Asia and the Pacific, 
Lin warned against the continued existence of unstable factors 
in the region such as hegemonism, power politics and wilful 
interference in others' internal affairs. 
  "It is imperative that all the countries concerned shall 
make 
arduous efforts to maintain comparative stability and preserve 
high- speed economic growth of the Asia-Pacific region in the 
1990s and even in the next century," she stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

