<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reports on President Clinton, Yeltsin Meetings </TI></H3>
<H4>   U.S., Russia, Ukraine Sign Accord </H4>
<F P=102> OW1401104994 Beijing XINHUA in English 0912 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1401104994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, January 14 (XINHUA) -- Russia, the United 
States and Ukraine signed here today a tripartite agreement on 
eliminating nuclear weapons on Ukrainian territory. 
  Well-informed sources told reporters that the accord was 
signed by Russian President Boris Yeltsin, U.S. President Bill 
Clinton and Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk in the Kremlin 
Palace this morning. 
  Meanwhile, the three leaders reaffirmed "the non-nuclear 
status of Ukraine and provided mechanisms of the withdrawal of 
nuclear warheads from Ukraine to Russia, as well as compensation 
to Ukraine for the warheads turned over to Russia," the sources 
said. 
  There are 176 nuclear missiles and about 1,500 warheads in 
the former second-largest Soviet Republic. 
  Yeltsin and Clinton told Kravchuk that "Russia and the 
United 
States will guarantee the security of Ukraine as a non-nuclear 
state," the sources added. 
  The three leaders began their tripartite summit talks at St. 
Catherine's Hall of the Grand Kremlin Palace at 09:00 a.m., and 
signed the accord in accordance with the results of the talks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

