<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reports on President Clinton, Yeltsin Meetings </TI></H3>
<H4>   Yeltsin Calls Visit `Successful' </H4>
<F P=102> OW1401124194 Beijing XINHUA in English 1124 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1401124194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, January 14 (XINHUA) -- Russian President 
Boris Yeltsin today described as successful U.S. President Bill 
Clinton's first official visit to Russia. 
  At a 50-minute joint news conference held in the press 
center 
of the Foreign Ministry, the Russian president stressed the 
visit was important for the United States as well as for Russia, 
saying it encouraged the "search for new components in the 
relations between the two countries." 
  Yeltsin said that he and Clinton effectively put an end to 
the Cold War in Vancouver and the two countries were now moving 
to "cooperation and partnership." 
  Touching upon the domestic situation in Russia, Yeltsin 
stressed that the adoption of a new constitution and the 
December 12 parliamentary elections were initial signs of 
success of the democratic process of Russia. 
  On December 12, the president said, the Russian people voted 
for "a better life." 
  Yeltsin also told reporters that Russia would keep reform 
going further and strengthen its social stability and peace. 

</TEXT>

