<H3> <TI>   Baltic Presidents View NATO Partnership Plan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1301015694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0145 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1301015694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Helsinki, January 12 (XINHUA) -- Presidents of 
three Baltic nations have warmly welcomed the "Partnership for 
Peace" plan agreed upon at the NATO summit and anticipated a 
bright prospect for their future NATO membership, the Finnish 
News Agency STT reported today. 
  In a joint statement, Estonian President Lennart Meri, 
Lithuanian President Algirdas Brazauskas and Latvian President 
Gontis Ulmanis expressed their appreciation of NATO's invitation 
to become associated with the organization within the boundaries 
of the "Partnership for Peace" proposal. 
  The plan provides for future cooperation between NATO and 
the 
Baltic states, they stressed, expressing hope that it could be 
realized. 
  The three presidents said that the cooperation between all 
European countries would enhance mutual trust and strengthen 
security in these areas. 

</TEXT>

