<F P=100> West Europe </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jiang Zemin Meets New French Ambassador </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK1401063294 Hong Kong AFP in English 0550 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> HK1401063294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, Jan 14 (AFP)--Chinese President Jiang 
Zemin welcomed Friday the resumption of normal relations between 
France and China and praised the foresight of Mao Zedong and 
former French president Charles de Gaulle in establishing ties 
30 years ago, a diplomatic source said. 
  Jiang made the remarks during a half-hour meeting with the 
new French ambassador, Francois Marcel Plaisant, who was 
presenting his credentials. 
  Plaisant was given the rare privilege of being received 
privately by the head of state. Normally a brief ceremony is 
held at which several ambassadors present their credentials at 
the same time. 
  Paris and Beijing issued a joint statement Wednesday 
normalising their relations and in which France undertook not to 
sell arms to Taiwan. Beijing claims sovereignty over the 
nationalist island. 
  Relations between Paris and Beijing had been in the doldrums 
for more than 14 months following France's decision to sell 
Mirage 2000- 5 jets to Taipei. 
  Jiang, who is also general secretary of the communist party, 
said that he admired French skills in the economic and 
technology fields, the diplomatic source added. 
  He also evoked the upcoming visit of French Prime Minister 
Edouard Balladur to China, expected to take place next month, 
and an official visit to France by Chinese Foreign Minister Qian 
Qichen. 
  Qian is currently on a tour of east Africa and is expected 
to 
visit Paris at the end of January. 

</TEXT>

