<F P=100> Northwest Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Qinghai Reports `Big Increase' in Exports </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1401014194 Beijing XINHUA in English 0106 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1401014194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Xining, January 14 (XINHUA) -- Northwest China's 
Qinghai Province, one of the country's most backward areas, saw 
a big increase in its exports in the past year. 
  According to local foreign trade officials, in 1993 the 
province clinched 101.74 million U.S. dollars in exports, 
fulfilling the state-set export quota for the province and also 
representing an increase of 12.51 percent over the previous year. 
  The officials attributed the initial success chiefly to the 
fact that relevant local departments helped export-oriented 
enterprises solve difficulties and some practical problems. 
Foreign trade departments also strived to make a success of the 
export of the province's traditional products, such as carpets 
and ferrosilicon, while endeavoring to develop new commodities 
in greater varieties for export. 
  So far, the province has 30 specialized foreign trade, 
economic and technical cooperation companies, and has 
established stable trade relations with more than 40 countries 
and regions in the world. The variety of commodities for export 
has increased from only nine kinds in 1980 to the present 120 
kinds in 12 categories. 

</TEXT>

