<F P=100> Science &amp; Technology </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seminars To Nurture Nation's Top Scientists </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK1201075494 Beijing CHINA DAILY in English 12 Jan 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> HK1201075494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing CHINA DAILY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By staff reporter Zhou Jie: "Seminars to Nurture Team of </F>
Top Scientists"] 
  [Text] China will hold more seminars to map out the 
strategic development of scientific research in the next century. 
  The Xiang Shan Conference, an annual high-level scientific 
meeting held in the Xiang Shan (Fragrant Hills) outside Beijing, 
will organize about 20 seminars this year compared with eight 
last year when it was first initiated and sponsored by the 
Chinese Academy of Sciences for discussing the direction of 
scientific research. 
  "The conference aims at foreseeing the development of 
frontier sciences, especially cross-discipline sciences," said 
Cao Xiaoye, of the organizing committee. 
  Cao said the organizing committee is requesting suggestions 
on seminar subjects nationwide. The first seminar this year is 
expected to be held in April. 
  Any Chinese scientists can apply to host or attend the 
conference. 
  "Foreign scientists and Chinese scientists working or 
studying abroad are also eligible to apply," Cao said. 
  Meanwhile, the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) is 
considering inviting some Nobel Prize winners to address the 
conference this year or next year. 
  The conference is part of the effort to make China one of 
the 
scientific powerhouses in the world. 
  Cao said that China has many good scientists, but needs some 
leading scientists who are capable of guiding the country's 
scientific research. 
  "Our conference is targeted at opening the minds of 
scientists and nurturing a group of leading scientists," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

