<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Banks `Prohibited' From Opening PRC Branches </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1401093694 Taipei CNA in English 0843 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1401093694 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Danielle Yang and Bear Li] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, Jan. 14 (CNA) -- Private Taiwan banks are 
still prohibited from setting up branches in Mainland China, a 
finance official said Friday [14 January]. 
  Deputy director Chang Hsiu-lien of the Finance Ministry's 
Bureau of Monetary Affairs said at a public hearing in the 
Legislative Yuan that the ban is in accordance with the initial 
stage of the Guidelines for National Unification. 
  Chang, however, said that a written evaluation on the 
feasibility of allowing private banks to set up branches in a 
third country is expected to be finished at the end of the year. 
  Chang made the remarks in response to growing demands by 
private bank officials to be allowed to set up on the mainland. 
The officials argue that increased cross-Taiwan Strait trade is 
making such service necessary. 
  Chang also said there is growing resistance in Mainland 
China 
to the establishment of Taiwan banks there. He said the 
mainland authorities are worried the Taiwan banks are more 
competitive than their mainland counterparts. 
  His statement was contradicted by a Friday report in the 
Hong 
Kong WEN WEI PO which said Beijing authorities in charge of 
Taiwan affairs have decided to allow the opening of 
Taiwan-invested banks in the mainland. 
  The Beijing-backed paper reported that the Beijing officials 
also decided to hold a national conference this spring to review 
progress in economic and trade exchanges with Taiwan and are 
mulling the formation of a State Council task force to 
coordinate Taiwan economic and trade policy. 
  The decision were reportedly made at a recent meeting 
attended by the heads of Beijing Central Government departments 
in charge of Taiwan affairs. 

</TEXT>

