<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Continued Reports on Hong Kong Airport Project </TI></H3>
<H4>   Patten on Airport Impasse </H4>
<F P=102> HK1401064294 Hong Kong THE STANDARD in English 14 Jan 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> HK1401064294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong THE STANDARD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Mary Binks, Political Editor] </F>
  [Text] Governor Chris Patten has again vented his 
frustration over almost two years of protracted negotiations on 
the financing of the new airport. The negotiations--already 
deadlocked--have become a casualty of the Sino-British fall-out 
over political reform. 
  "What would help us a great deal is to be in a situation in 
which we didn't feel as though we're playing darts blindfold in 
the dark, hoping to hit the bull's-eye," he said. 
  "What would be a help would be if the Chinese side gave 
precisely what funding arrangements they would regard as 
acceptable. 
  "These funds would help in the future of the Special 
Administrative Region (SAR) government the community here in 
Hong Kong and for the railway and the airport itself." 
  Patten voiced concern that the airport negotiations were 
becoming bogged down by obscure political bickering and he again 
urged the Chinese to return to the negotiating table. "We could 
rapidly resolve all that I would have hoped in the airport 
committee if the will was there." 
  It is now unlikely the airport project will be completed by 
mid- 1997, but rather months after the transfer of sovereignty. 
  "Instead of offering one another advice across the airwaves, 
we should actually do what people in Hongkong would like us to 
do which is to resolve these questions around the table," he 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

