<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Macao </F>
<H3> <TI>   Check Point in Operation on China, Macao Border </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1201163394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1522 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1201163394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Macao, January 12 (XINHUA) -- The frontier post 
(check point) at the barrier gate of Macao, a gateway through 
which passengers can go directly into China's mainland, was put 
into official use today. 
  The old barrier gate will be protected as cultural relics 
and 
a tourism spot from now on. 
  After the frontier post was put into operation, passengers 
come and leave Macao will have to go through the entry and exit 
passages of the post. All entry and exit procedures will remain 
unchanged. 
  Costing more than 30 million Macao patacas (about 3.8 
million 
U.S. dollars), construction of the frontier post started in 1990 
and it was first put into initial use in February 1993. 
  During last year's February-November period, there were more 
than 15.37 million passengers going through the post and there 
were also 1.06 million freight cars passing the post in the same 
period. 
  The barrier gate is the only passage in Macao leading to 
China's mainland on land. It is connected with Gongbei of 
Zhuhai city, south China's Guangdong Province. 
  Macao Governor General Vasco Joaquim Rocha Vieira, Guo 
Dongpo, director of the XINHUA NEWS AGENCY Macao branch, and 
many noted personages in Macao participated in today's ceremony 
for the inauguration of the frontier post. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

