<F P=100> Latin America &amp; Caribbean </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports on Cuban Airliner Defection </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0601013194 Beijing XINHUA in English 0117 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0601013194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Havana, January 5 (XINHUA) -- The Cuban Air Charter 
Company denied today that the whole crew of an Aerocaribbean 
Airliner defected in Great Cayman Island. 
  Cuba's official news agency, PRENSA LATINA, said 
vice-president of the air charter company Pedro Manduley 
confirmed that the copilot of the plane chose not to return to 
Cuba and was detained by the Caribbean island immigration 
authorities. 
  The DC-3, with 11 tourists aboard, flying the Havana-Great 
Cayman-Havana route, was bound for the capital during the next 
hours, said the Cuban official. 
  After the incident occurred Tuesday [4 January], the captain 
of the aircraft and three crew members called the main offices 
of the Aerocaribbean Tuesday night to ask for authorized return 
flight. 
  According to international rules, no aircraft can fly 
without 
a copilot. As a result, the return was postponed until today 
after another copilot was flown in a company plane to Great 
Cayman, said Manduley. 

</TEXT>

