<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Guangdong Attempts To `Improve' Labor Relations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1301064194 Beijing XINHUA in English 0610 GMT 13 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1301064194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guangzhou, January 13 (XINHUA) -- With the 
deepening of reforms, this capital of south China's Guangdong 
Province is making new efforts to improve the relations between 
labor and capital. 
  In Guangzhou today, more and more enterprises under various 
economic ownerships are taking shape, including over 6,000 
foreign-funded enterprises. They make labor-capital relations 
more complex, according to Du Meixian, vice president of the 
Guangzhou Federation of Trade Unions. 
  To effectively protect the interests of both sides, the city 
government is hammering out relevant regulations and setting up 
supervision and arbitration organizations. Trade unions inside 
enterprises are playing their part in mediating disputes. 
  In 1993, the city government worked out a decree which set 
the minimum worker's salary at 250 yuan a month. 
  On the other hand, the city advocates workers associating 
themselves more closely with the rise and fall of their 
enterprises. 
  Every year, the city will commend a large number of 
outstanding workers, factory directors, company managers and 
trade union leaders. 

</TEXT>

