<F P=100> Southwest Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sichuan Court on Economic Disputes With Foreigners </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1201135694 Beijing XINHUA in English 1338 GMT 12 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1201135694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Chongqing, January 12 (XINHUA) -- The economic 
section under the Sichuan intermediate court, with the task of 
handling economic disputes involving overseas clients, was set 
up today in Chongqing, the largest economic center in southwest 
China. 
  This overseas-related economic court is the first of its 
kind 
founded in Sichuan Province. 
  Along with the expanding of reform and opening, more and 
more 
economic disputes have surfaced involving foreign-funded 
enterprises and Sino-foreign joint ventures as well as investors 
from Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan. 
  By the end of last year, the city had 1,300 overseas-funded 
businesses. 
  Early in 1977, China's first economic court was set up in 
Chongqing. The Sichuan intermediate court began to prepare for 
the foundation of an economic court to handle disputes involving 
overseas clients April last year. 
  During the preparatory period, the court took up 19 economic 
cases, involving 37 million yuan and 2.3 million U.S. dollars. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

