<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Views European `Partnership for Peace' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1401163894 Beijing XINHUA in English 1514 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1401163894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, January 14 (XINHUA) -- Russian President 
Boris Yeltsin said today that the U.S. proposal on establishing 
a "partnership for peace" with former Eastern Bloc countries may 
prove only "one of the scenarios for building a new Europe." 
  Speaking at a joint press conference with U.S. President 
Bill 
Clinton, Yeltsin said Russia will "keep track" of other security 
structures in Europe, including the United Nations and the 
Conference on Security and Cooperation in Europe (CSCE). 
  Yeltsin also said that one should not be fearful of 
"imperial 
ambitions" in Russia, because Russia is only interested in 
stability, and will try to eliminate the chance of conflict 
along the new borders between former Soviet republics. 
  He complained of the failure of some countries to respond to 
Russia's proposal for ending the conflicts in Nagorno-Karabakh 
and Tajikstan. 
  Yeltsin also warned that a "double standard" should not be 
used by Western countries in their relations with Russia and the 
Baltic republics. 
  "No double standard should be allowed here... in Haiti or 
the 
Baltics," he said. "To that end we adopted a very forceful 
declaration on securing human rights... so that no more 
discrimination will be allowed against the Russian-speaking 
population in the Baltics." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

