<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   Visit by Richard Gephart, Delegation Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   MFN Status Discussed </H4>
<F P=102> OW1501093794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0916 GMT 15 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1501093794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, January 15 (XINHUA) -- The Chinese National 
People's Congress (NPC) wishes to enhance its exchanges and 
cooperation with the U.S. Congress so as to jointly promote the 
healthy growth of Sino-U.S. relations. 
  NPC Standing Committee Chairman Qiao Shi expressed the wish 
when meeting with Richard Gephardt, visiting majority leader of 
the House of Representatives of the United States. 
  Extending his welcome to Gephardt and his party, Qiao said 
that many U.S. congressmen had visited China since last November 
when Chinese President Jiang Zemin and U.S. President Bill 
Clinton met in Seattle, which was regarded as a new start in 
bilateral relations. 
  Such visits have helped promote the congressmen's 
understanding of China, and provided opportunities for exchanges 
of views on issues of common concern. 
  On the issue of the most-favored-nation (MFN) trading 
status, 
Qiao said that the MFN treatment is an arrangement of equity and 
mutual benefit between China and the United States. 
  He reiterated that China is against linking the MFN 
treatment 
with issues that have nothing to do with trade, such as the 
human rights issue. 
  Qiao said that a sound political, economic and trade 
relationship between the two countries is in line with the 
fundamental interests of the two peoples and is conducive to 
world peace and development. 
  Gephardt said that U.S.-Chinese relations are "most 
essential" to the two countries and to the rest of the world as 
well. 
  He said he believed that dialogues and exchanges would 
improve U.S.-Chinese ties, adding that the United States hopes 
progress would be achieved in bilateral relations. 
  The U.S. guests arrived in China Wednesday [12 January] at 
the invitation of the Chinese People's Institute of Foreign 
Affairs. 

</TEXT>

