<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   Visit by Richard Gephart, Delegation Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Jiang `Welcomes' Congressmen </H4>
<F P=102> CM1801150894 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 1048 
GMT 15 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> CM1801150894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, January 15 (XINHUA) -- China's President 
Jiang Zemin said this afternoon at Zhongnanhai that China 
welcomes more congressmen visiting the country and hopes they 
will do more to enhance mutual understanding and to improve ties 
between China and the United States. 
  Jiang made the remarks at a meeting with a visiting U.S. 
six-member delegation from the House of Representatives, led by 
majority leader Richard Gephardt. 
  The U.S. Congress has a unique role to play in the making of 
U.S. domestic and foreign policies, Jiang said, adding that it 
can exert its influence in promoting the development of 
Sino-U.S. ties. 
  Since last year, more than 100 U.S. congressmen have visited 
China. Jiang said that the visits would help them to learn 
about China's real situation and to make right decisions 
regarding Sino-U.S. ties. 
  The past few years have witnessed fruitful Sino-U.S. 
economic 
and trade cooperation, he said, and it has been proved that 
China and the U.S. are highly complementary to each other in the 
economic and trade fields and they have wide spheres of 
cooperation. 
  Gephardt said that the U.S. and China are two great nations. 
It is of great significance for leaders of the two countries to 
maintain their contacts. He added that active relations looking 
to the future should be developed between the two countries. 
  Gephardt said he learned a lot about China during the 
current 
trip and saw major positive changes in the country's economic 
sphere. 
  The U.S. is looking forward to developing more successful 
and 
closer ties with China, he said. 
  Among those taking part in the meeting were Liu Shuqing, 
president of the Chinese People's Institute of Foreign Affairs, 
Chinese Vice-Foreign Minister Liu Huaqiu and U.S. Ambassador to 
China Stapleton Roy. 
  This morning, Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji also met Gephardt and 
the other U.S. congressmen. 

</TEXT>

