<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S., Sino Textile Talks Underway in Beijing </TI></H3>
<H4>   XINHUA Views Accord </H4>
<F P=102> OW1801010294 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 1355 
GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1801010294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporters Zhang Yijun (1728 4135 0193) and Jiang Jun </F>
(1203 6511); Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese at 1618 
GMT on 17 January transmits a service message correcting the 
following item; differences between the two versions are noted 
below] 
  [Text] Beijing, 17 Jan (XINHUA) -- Representatives of the 
Chinese and U.S. Governments concluded and reached agreement on 
the fourth round of negotiations on bilateral textile trade 
talks. 
  Shi Guangsheng, Chinese vice minister of foreign trade and 
economic relations, and Ambassador Jennifer Hillman, U.S. Trade 
Representative Office chief negotiator for textile talks, signed 
a memorandum of understanding on a bilateral textile trade 
agreement on behalf of their respective governments. 
  Shi Guangsheng told reporters at the conclusion of the 
negotiations that [corrected version reads: ...According to a 
briefing.... (rewording)], both China and the United States made 
concessions during the latest round of negotiations. The U.S. 
side has agreed not to insist on reductions of between 25 and 35 
percent in import quotas of Chinese textiles; it has also 
withdrawn articles of arbitrary deduction regarding illegal 
transshipment of textiles. The Chinese side also made 
substantial concessions during the talks. China has agreed to 
accept a quota reduction of no more than three times the amount 
of textiles conclusively proven to have been illegally 
transshipped by Chinese traders. Furthermore, China also agreed 
to major adjustments of some categories of the textile quota 
proposed by the U.S. side. 
  The third Chinese-U.S. textile agreement expired on 31 
December 1993. To negotiate and sign the fourth agreement, 
China and the United States conducted three rounds of talks 
without success from September to December last year. 
  Shi Guangsheng said [corrected version reads: ...It is 
understood.... (rewording)] that during the fourth round of 
talks, both sides took into consideration the overall interests 
of bilateral trade and economic ties, and adhered to the 
principle of equality, consultation and mutual understanding, 
and accommodation, thereby reaching agreement on textile 
arrangements -- an issue of great concern for both sides. The 
signing of the new agreement will be conducive to the healthy 
development of textile trade as well as other economic and trade 
ties between the two countries. 
  Wu Yi, minister of foreign trade and economic cooperation, 
witnessed the signing ceremony and met with the U.S. delegation 
led by Ambassador Hillman. She said: China attaches great 
importance to developing cooperation with the United States in 
economic, trade, and other areas. The United States has 
capital, technology, and equipment, which are conducive to 
China's modernization drive, while China has a huge market and 
abundant source of labor. The two countries are economically 
complementary. 
  Wu Yi said: Various problems, difficulties, and 
contradictions may arise in the course of cooperation between 
the two sides. However, it has been proved by years of practice 
that the best way to address these problems is through dialogue 
and consultation on an equal footing. Any attempt to exert 
pressure by one side on the other will be futile and can only 
lead to a trade war, which we do not want to see happen. 
  Wu Yi said: China and the United States share an identical 
view and common interests in cracking down on illegal 
transshipment of textiles. It is hoped that both sides will 
further cooperate and take measures to ensure a smooth 
implementation of the memorandum of understanding on the 
bilateral textile agreement. 
  Hillman said the Sino-U.S. negotiations were productive, 
cooperative, and mutually satisfactory. She added that China is 
the largest exporter of textiles to the United States, and the 
just concluded agreement is "extremely important" for developing 
economic and trade relations between the two countries. 

</TEXT>

