<H3> <TI>   Meets Sudanese President </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1501195294 Beijing XINHUA in English 1931 GMT 15 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1501195294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Khartoum, January 15 (XINHUA) -- 'Umar Hassan Ahmad 
al-Bashir, president of Republic of Sudan, met with the visiting 
Chinese Vice Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen here this 
afternoon. 
  Al-Bashir said during the meeting that Sudan and China have 
strong, traditional and friendly ties. He hoped to promote the 
bilateral political and economic relations and increase the 
visits of officials and non-government personnel between the two 
countries. 
  The Sudanese president also focused the strengthening of 
economic and technological cooperation between the two countries 
in the new world situation. 
  Al-Bashir said Sudan is a big market. He welcomed the 
investment from Chinese enterprisers and the establishment of 
companies in various fields. 
  Qian Qichen, on his leg of six-nation African tour, said his 
visit aimed at further promoting the Sino-Sudanese relations. 
  He expressed satisfaction at political, economic and 
cultural 
developments between the two countries. 
  He said Sudan is among the first group of countries that 
established diplomatic relations with China. The relations 
between the two countries have been healthy and have not been 
affected by the changes in the international communities. 
  Qian conveyed Chinese President Jiang Zemin's greetings to 
the Sudanese president during the meeting. 
  The Chinese foreign minister also held a talk with his 
Sudanese counterpart Husayn Sulayman Abu-Salih later today. 
  Qian's six-nation tour has already taken him to Ethiopia and 
Eritrea and will continue on to Kenya, Madagascar and Mauritius. 
  The Chinese vice premier and foreign minister left Khartoum 
this evening for Kenya. 

</TEXT>

