<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Agricultural Bank To Continue `Mandatory Lending' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK1701001694 Beijing CHINA DAILY (BUSINESS WEEKLY) in 
English 16-22 Jan 94 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> HK1701001694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing CHINA DAILY (BUSINESS WEEKLY) </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Farm Bank Affirms Its Loan Policy] </F>
  [Text] The Agricultural Bank of China, the country's 
leading bank for rural investment, will continue its policy of 
mandatory lending this year, its president said. 
  The bank president, Ma Yongwei, said last week at a national 
conference of bankers that the bank will control its lending 
according to the policies of the central bank, the People's Bank 
of China. 
  Ma said that this year the bank will continue its mandated 
lending to support the State's plan for developing rural 
industry and the fixed assets in the countryside. 
  In response to the growing demand for capital for the 
countryside, Ma said, the bank's arranged loans this year for 
various sectors in the rural economy are expected to surpass 
last year's. 
  But because a market economy requires the country's lending 
institutions to operate more commercially, the bank must also 
consider the risks in extending credit, Ma said. 
  In a firm response to the government's call for strongly 
backing agriculture, the bank intends this year to expand loans 
for crop production by 25 billion yuan ($2.87 billion) from last 
year, when it lent about 233 billion yuan ($26.78 billion). 
  Ma predicted that in 1994 inflation will exert greater 
pressure on farmers to cut production costs. If inflation 
remains at last year's level, he said, it will stimulate a 
rising spiral in agricultural prices as well as in the demand 
for bank loans. 
  In addition, Ma said the disparity between available capital 
and the demand for credit will widen this year as the 
Agricultural Bank must shoulder a heavier burden in buying State 
Treasury bonds and co-operated bonds. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-45328 </DOCNO>
