<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia To Sell Enriched Uranium to U.S. </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1401163994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1611 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1401163994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, January 14 (XINHUA) -- Russia agreed today 
to sell 12 billion U.S. dollars worth of highly enriched uranium 
over the next 20 years to the United States, and a senior 
Russian official hailed the deal as "a real move towards genuine 
nuclear disarmament." 
  Under the agreement, signed here during the summit meeting 
between Russian President Boris Yeltsin and U.S. President Bill 
Clinton, the U.S. will buy 500 tons of highly enriched uranium 
from dismantled nuclear warheads. 
  As many as 20,000 nuclear warheads would have to be 
dismantled in Russia and Ukraine to provide the agreed amount of 
enriched uranium to the United States, which plans to distribute 
it for use among its 15 nuclear reactors. 
  Russia will receive foreign currency from the transaction, 
and Russia, Ukraine, Belarus and Kazakhstan will share in the 
profits. 
  "The agreement means a real move toward genuine nuclear 
disarmament," Russian Atomic Energy Minister Viktor Mikhailov 
said, while the U.S. pointed out that this will be the first 
time in history that disarmament brings profit to some countries. 
  Announcement of the uranium sale followed the nuclear 
disarmament agreement between the United States, Russia, and 
Ukraine signed by Clinton, Yeltsin and Ukrainian President 
Leonid Kravchuk earlier today. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

