<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Visit by Former President Bush </TI></H3>
<H4>   Views World Events With Li Peng </H4>
<F P=102> OW1401133894 Beijing XINHUA in English 1331 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1401133894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, January 14 (XINHUA) -- Premier Li Peng and 
visiting former U.S. President George Bush had a 40-minute 
discussion on Sino-U.S. Relations and the international 
situation this evening. 
  Bush last visited China in February 1989. 
  Li welcomed Bush for his current tour in China and expressed 
appreciation for his efforts to uphold the framework of 
Sino-U.S. relations and his correct decision to renew China`s 
most-favored- nation trading status. 
  Li hoped that Sino-U.S. relations will continue to improve 
and develop on the basis of mutual respect and seeking common 
ground while reserving differences. 
  Briefing Bush on China's reform and opening drive, Li said 
that the Chinese people, guided by Comrade Deng Xiaoping's 
theory of building socialism with Chinese characteristics, have 
chosen a way to development fitting China's reality. 
  He emphasized that the 15-year-old reform and opening drive 
shows that so long as China sticks to its course, it will enjoy 
economic development and political stability. 
  "A stable, developing and prosperous China is a big 
contribution to world peace and development," Li said. 
  Bush told Li, that during his current revisit in Beijing 
after five years he was greatly impressed by the great changes 
he witnessed in China, and China's economic success. 
  He will continue to work to further U.S.-China relations, he 
added. 
  After the meeting, Li Peng hosted a dinner in honor of Bush. 
  Among those taking part in the meeting and dinner were Qi 
Huaiyuan, director of the Office of Foreign Affairs of the State 
Council, Liu Huaqiu, vice-foreign minister, and General Brent 
Scowcroft, former assistant to the President for national 
security affairs. 
  Luo Gan, State Councillor and secretary-general of the State 
Council, met with Bush earlier today. 

</TEXT>

