<F P=100> Taiwan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Import Tariff Cuts Possible Prior to U.S. Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1701091694 Taipei CNA in English 0802 GMT 17 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1701091694 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Bear Li] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, Jan. 17 (CNA) -- Economic Affairs Minister 
P.K. Chiang said Monday [17 January] that Taiwan may 
unilaterally lower import tariffs prior to holding tariff 
consultations with the United States Jan. 19-20. 
  The move will help Taiwan avoid additional tariff cuts 
during 
later negotiations about Taiwan's entry to the General Agreement 
on Tariffs and Trade (GATT), Chiang said after meeting with 
visiting British Deputy Secretary of Trade and Industry 
Christopher Roberts. 
  The United States has asked Taiwan to cut tariffs on 699 
farm 
and industrial products by as much as 50 percent. U.S. 
negotiators have also been opposed to a Taiwan suggestion that 
the tariff cuts be included as part of expected GATT-related 
tariff cuts. 
  If Taiwan gives in to both U.S. and GATT demands, Chiang 
said, Taiwan would have to cut import tariffs twice. 
  However, a unilateral tariff reduction prior to negotiations 
with the U.S. would effectively help minimize any undesirable 
impact, Chiang added. 
  Meanwhile, Director-General Huang Yen-chao of the Board of 
Foreign Trade left Taiwan Monday for Washington, D.C., where he 
will take part in tariff negotiations with U.S. Trade 
Representative Office officials. 
  Huang said prior to his departure that government agencies 
have concluded that Taiwan can allow tariff cuts for only 10 
percent of the industrial products requested by the United 
States, and tariffs will not be reduced on any agricultural 
items. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-45344 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi011_v_94005" </HT>


