<F P=100> Taiwan </F>
<H3> <TI>   MAC Agrees To Emergency Landings on Mainland </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1401144694 Taipei CNA in English 1406 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1401144694 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Benjamin Yeh] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, Jun. 14 (CNA) -- The Mainland Affairs 
Council (MAC) on Friday [14 January] agreed to a request by a 
local airline [words indistinct] demanded that their passenger 
airplanes bound for [words indistinct] permitted to make 
emergency landing in mainland China. 
  MAC Vice Chairman Kao Kung-lien told the press that his 
council has no intention to intervene in emergency landings. 
"The request is merely for safety considerations...it has 
nothing to do with the establishment of direct air links with 
the mainland," Kao stressed. 
  Formosa Airlines will begin flight service from Taipei to 
Matsu on Jan. 17. Matsu is about 10 nautical miles off the 
coast of Mainland China. 
  The airline asked the Ministry of Transportation and 
Communications to make the emergency landing request to the 
mainland authority. 
  A ministry official, however, asserted that the likelihood 
of 
landing on the mainland is small as long as pilots fly planes in 
accordance with standard procedures required by the Civil 
Aeronautics Administration. 

</TEXT>

