<F P=100> Taiwan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Loans Vietnam $10 Million </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1501102994 Taipei CNA in English 0838 GMT 15 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1501102994 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Sofia Wu] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, Jan. 15 (CNA) -- The Republic of China 
[ROC] will lend an additional US$10 million to Vietnam to help 
the Indochinese country build an industrial park in Hanoi to 
house Taiwan-invested factories, Vice Economic Affairs Minister 
Sheu Ke-sheng said Saturday [15 January]. 
  "The move proves that our government attaches great 
importance to strengthening trade and economic cooperation 
[words indistinct] Vietnam," said Sheu, who returned to Taipei 
Thursday from a visit to Hanoi. 
  The five-year loan, with an interest rate of 7 percent per 
annum, will be administered by the Vietnamese central bank to 
help Taiwan land developers build a 200-hectare industrial zone 
in Vietnam's capital city, Sheu noted. 
  The money will come from the International Economic 
Cooperation and Development Fund established by the ROC 
Government in 1989 to offer financial aid to needy developing 
countries. 
  Taiwan has already lent Vietnam US$30 million to expand a 
highway and another US$15 million to fund the development of 
small- and medium-sized Vietnamese companies. 
  The planned Hanoi industrial park will be the second such 
zone Taiwan has helped build in Vietnam. A similar industrial 
park has been set up in Ho Chi Minh City to house 
Taiwan-invested firms. 
  There are some 700 Taiwan-invested companies in Ho Chi Minh 
City and more than 40 local manufacturers have expressed 
intention to set up production lines in Hanoi, Sheu reported. 
  Taiwan businessmen have poured more than US$1.2 billion for 
various investment projects in Vietnam since the late 1980s, 
making Taiwan one of Vietnam's major foreign capital source. 
  Sheu said the government will send investment officials to 
Vietnam in the near future to help that country simplify its 
investment procedures. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

