<F P=100> PRC MEDIA ON TAIWAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Forum Views Deng's `One Country, Two Systems' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1401160194 Beijing XINHUA in English 1449 GMT 14 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1401160194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, January 14 (XINHUA) -- The Taiwan Affairs 
Office under the State Council today held a forum to discuss 
Deng Xiaoping's scientific thought of "peaceful reunification" 
and "one country, two systems". 
  Wang Zhaoguo, director of the Taiwan Affairs Office, said 
the 
principle of "one country, two systems" is the concrete 
application of Marxism in contemporary China. 
  Wang, also vice-chairman of the National Committee of the 
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference, said that it 
is the outcome of the party's line of seeking truth from fact 
and constitutes one important part of the theory of building 
socialism with Chinese characteristics. 
  He called for earnest study and implementation of Deng's 
idea 
of "peaceful reunification" of the motherland and "one country, 
two systems", adherence to the one China principle, safeguarding 
China's sovereignty and territorial integrity, and opposition to 
any advocacy of "two Chinas", "one China, one Taiwan" and 
"Taiwan independence". 
  Wang Daohan, chairman of the Association of the Relations 
Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS), said that his association 
aims to develop the exchanges and relations across the Taiwan 
Straits and to promote peaceful reunification of the motherland. 
  He said that with the approach of the 21st century, the 
Mainland and Taiwan should enhance their economic cooperation to 
attain mutual benefits. 
  Cai Zimin, chairman of the Central Committee of the Taiwan 
Democratic Self-Government League, said that the Taiwan people 
have a patriotic tradition which remains unchanged. 
  He said that the principle of "one country, two systems" 
respects the realities on the two sides across the Taiwan 
Straits and agrees with the Taiwan compatriots' wish for being 
their own masters. 
  He said that the claims for "two Chinas" and "one China, one 
Taiwan" advocated by some people in Taiwan or outside Taiwan are 
doomed to fail. 

</TEXT>

